{"title_page": "June 13", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\n==Events==\n* [[313]] &ndash; The decisions of the [[Edict of Milan]], signed by [[Constantine the Great]] and co-emperor [[Licinius|Valerius Licinius]], granting [[religious freedom]] throughout the [[Roman Empire]], are published in [[Nicomedia]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Harold W. Attridge|author2=G\u014dhei Hata|title=Eusebius, Christianity, and Judaism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jVyzbHAJ_hAC&pg=PA645|year=1992|publisher=Wayne State University Press|isbn=0-8143-2361-8|pages=645}}</ref>\n*[[1381]] &ndash; In England, the [[Peasants' Revolt]], led by [[Wat Tyler]], comes to a head, as rebels set fire to the [[Savoy Palace]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Church Historical Society (Great Britain).|title=Typical English Churchmen: From Wyclif to Gardiner|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tKIzAQAAIAAJ|year=1909|publisher=Society for Promoting Christian Knowledge|page=92}}</ref>\n*[[1514]] &ndash; ''[[Henry Grace \u00e0 Dieu]]'', at over 1,000 tons the largest [[warship]] in the world at this time, built at the new [[Woolwich Dockyard]] in England, is dedicated.\n*[[1525]] &ndash; [[Martin Luther]] marries [[Katharina von Bora]], against the [[celibacy]] rule decreed by the Roman Catholic Church for priests and nuns.\n*[[1625]] &ndash; King [[Charles I of England]] marries Catholic princess [[Henrietta Maria of France]] and [[Navarre]], at Canterbury.\n*[[1740]] &ndash; [[Province of Georgia|Georgia]] provincial governor [[James Oglethorpe]] begins an unsuccessful attempt to take [[Spanish Florida]] during the [[Siege of St. Augustine (1740)|Siege of St. Augustine]].\n*[[1774]] &ndash; [[Rhode Island]] becomes the first of Britain's North American colonies to ban the importation of slaves.\n*[[1777]] &ndash; [[American Revolutionary War]]: [[Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette]] lands near [[Charleston, South Carolina]], in order to help the [[Continental Congress]] to train its army.\n*[[1805]] &ndash; [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]]: scouting ahead of the expedition, [[Meriwether Lewis]] and four companions sight the [[Great Falls of the Missouri River]].\n*[[1881]] &ndash; The [[USS Jeannette (1878)|USS ''Jeannette'']] is crushed in an Arctic Ocean ice pack.\n*[[1886]] &ndash; [[Great Vancouver Fire|A fire devastates]] much of [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].\n*[[1893]] &ndash; [[Grover Cleveland]] notices a rough spot in his mouth and on July 1 undergoes [[Grover Cleveland#Cancer|secret, successful surgery]] to remove a large, cancerous portion of his jaw; the operation was not revealed to the public until 1917, nine years after the president's death.\n*[[1898]] &ndash; [[Yukon Territory]] is formed, with [[Dawson, Yukon|Dawson]] chosen as its capital.\n*[[1917]] &ndash; [[World War I]]: The deadliest [[German strategic bombing during World War I|German air raid on London]] of the war is carried out by [[Gotha G.IV]] bombers and results in 162 deaths, including 46 children, and 432 injuries. \n*[[1927]] &ndash; Aviator [[Charles Lindbergh]] receives a [[ticker tape parade]] down 5th Avenue in New York City.\n*[[1944]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: The [[Battle of Villers-Bocage]]:  German tank ace [[Michael Wittmann]] ambushes elements of the [[British 7th Armoured Division]], destroying up to fourteen tanks, fifteen personnel carriers and two anti-tank guns in a [[Tiger I]] tank.\n*  1944   &ndash; World War II: German combat elements, reinforced by the [[17th SS Panzergrenadier Division]], [[Battle of Bloody Gulch|launch a counterattack]] on American forces near [[Carentan]].\n*  1944   &ndash; World War II: Germany launches the first [[V1 Flying Bomb]] attack on England. Only four of the eleven bombs strike their targets.\n*[[1952]] &ndash; [[Catalina affair]]: A Swedish [[Douglas DC-3]] is shot down by a Soviet [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-15|MiG-15]] fighter.\n*[[1966]] &ndash; The [[United States Supreme Court]] rules in ''[[Miranda v. Arizona]]'' that the police must inform suspects of their rights before questioning them.\n*[[1967]] &ndash; U.S. President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] nominates Solicitor-General [[Thurgood Marshall]] to become the first black justice on the [[U.S. Supreme Court]].\n*[[1971]] &ndash; [[Vietnam War]]: ''[[The New York Times]]'' begins publication of the ''[[Pentagon Papers]]''.\n*[[1977]] &ndash; Convicted [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] assassin [[James Earl Ray]] is recaptured after escaping from prison three days before.\n*[[1981]] &ndash; At the [[Trooping the Colour]] ceremony in London, a teenager, [[Marcus Sarjeant]], fires six blank shots at Queen [[Elizabeth II]].\n*[[1982]] &ndash; [[Fahd of Saudi Arabia|Fahd]] becomes [[King of Saudi Arabia]] upon the death of his brother, [[Khalid of Saudi Arabia|Khalid]].\n*  1982   &ndash; Battles of [[Battle of Mount Tumbledown|Tumbledown]] and [[Battle of Wireless Ridge|Wireless Ridge]], during the [[Falklands War]].\n*[[1983]] &ndash; ''[[Pioneer 10]]'' becomes the first man-made object to leave the central [[Solar System]] when it passes beyond the orbit of [[Neptune]].\n*[[1990]] &ndash; First day of the [[June 1990 Mineriad]] in Romania. At least 240 strikers and students are arrested or killed in the chaos ensuing from the first post-[[Nicolae Ceau\u0219escu|Ceau\u0219escu]] elections.\n*[[1994]] &ndash; A jury in [[Anchorage, Alaska]], blames recklessness by [[Exxon]] and Captain [[Joseph Hazelwood]] for the ''[[Exxon Valdez]]'' disaster, allowing victims of the oil spill to seek $15 billion in damages.\n*[[1996]] &ndash; The [[Montana Freemen]] surrender after an 81-day standoff with [[FBI]] agents.\n*[[1997]] &ndash; A jury sentences [[Timothy McVeigh]] to death for his part in the [[1995]] [[Oklahoma City bombing]].\n*[[2000]] &ndash; President [[Kim Dae-jung]] of South Korea meets [[Kim Jong-il]], leader of [[North Korea]], for the beginning of the first ever [[Inter-Korean summits|inter-Korea summit]], in the northern capital of [[Pyongyang]].\n*  2000   &ndash; Italy pardons [[Mehmet Ali A\u011fca]], the Turkish gunman who tried to kill [[Pope John Paul II]] in 1981.\n*[[2002]] &ndash; The United States withdraws from the [[Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty]].\n*[[2007]] &ndash; The [[Al Askari Mosque]] is [[2007 al-Askari Mosque bombing|bombed for a second time]].\n*[[2010]] &ndash; A capsule of the Japanese spacecraft ''[[Hayabusa]]'', containing particles of the asteroid [[25143 Itokawa]], returns to Earth.\n*[[2012]] &ndash; A [[13 June 2012 Iraq attacks|series of bombings]] across [[Iraq]], including [[Baghdad]], [[Hillah]] and [[Kirkuk]], kills at least 93 people and wounds over 300 others.\n*[[2015]] &ndash; A man [[2015 attack on Dallas police|opens fire]] at policemen outside the [[Dallas Police Department|police headquarters in Dallas, Texas]], while a bag containing a [[pipe bomb]] is also found. He was later shot dead by police.\n\n==Births==\n*[[AD 40]]&ndash; [[Gnaeus Julius Agricola]], Roman general (d. 93)\n*[[823]]  &ndash; [[Charles the Bald]], Holy Roman Emperor (d. 877)\n* [[839]] &ndash; [[Charles the Fat]], Holy Roman Emperor (d. 888)\n*[[1367]] &ndash; [[Taejong of Joseon]] (d. 1422)\n*[[1500]] &ndash; [[Ernest of Bavaria (1500\u20131560)|Ernest of Bavaria]], pledge lord of the County of Glatz (d. 1560)\n*[[1508]] &ndash; [[Alessandro Piccolomini]], Italian astronomer and philosopher (d. 1579)\n*[[1539]] &ndash; [[Jost Amman]], Swiss printmaker (d. 1591)\n*[[1555]] &ndash; [[Giovanni Antonio Magini]], Italian mathematician, cartographer and astronomer (d. 1617)\n*[[1580]] &ndash; [[Willebrord Snell]], Dutch astronomer and mathematician (d. 1626)\n*[[1595]] &ndash; [[Jan Marek Marci]], Czech physician and scientist (d. 1667)\n*[[1617]] &ndash; [[Sir Vincent Corbet, 1st Baronet]], English politician (d. 1656)\n*[[1649]] &ndash; [[Adrien Baillet]], French scholar and critic (d. 1706)\n*[[1711]] &ndash; [[Sir Richard Glyn, 1st Baronet, of Ewell]], English banker and politician, [[Lord Mayor of London]] (d. 1773)\n*[[1752]] &ndash; [[Frances Burney]], English novelist and playwright (d. 1840)\n*[[1761]] &ndash; [[Anton\u00edn Vranick\u00fd]], Czech violinist and composer (d. 1820)\n*[[1763]] &ndash; [[Jos\u00e9 Bonif\u00e1cio de Andrada]], Brazilian poet, academic, and politician (d. 1838)\n*[[1773]] &ndash; [[Thomas Young (scientist)|Thomas Young]], English physicist and physiologist (d. 1829)\n*[[1775]] &ndash; [[Antoni Radziwi\u0142\u0142]], Polish-Lithuanian composer and politician (d. 1833)\n*[[1786]] &ndash; [[Winfield Scott]], American general (d. 1866)\n*[[1790]] &ndash; [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio P\u00e1ez]], Venezuelan general and politician, [[List of Presidents of Venezuela|President of Venezuela]] (d. 1873)\n*[[1809]] &ndash; [[Heinrich Hoffmann (author)|Heinrich Hoffmann]], German psychiatrist and author (d. 1894)\n*[[1822]] &ndash; [[Carl Schmidt (chemist)|Carl Schmidt]], Latvian-German chemist and academic (d. 1894)\n*[[1827]] &ndash; [[Alberto Henschel]], German-Brazilian photographer and businessman (d. 1882)\n*[[1831]] &ndash; [[James Clerk Maxwell]], Scottish physicist and mathematician (d. 1879)\n*[[1840]] &ndash; [[Augusta Lundin]], the first international Swedish fashion designer (d. 1919)\n*[[1854]] &ndash; [[Charles Algernon Parsons]], English engineer, founded [[C. A. Parsons and Company]] (d. 1931)\n*[[1863]] &ndash; [[Lucy, Lady Duff-Gordon]], English fashion designer (d. 1935)\n*[[1864]] &ndash; [[Rudolf Kjell\u00e9n]], Swedish political scientist and academic (d. 1922)\n*  1864   &ndash; [[Dwight B. Waldo]], American historian and academic (d. 1939)\n*[[1865]] &ndash; [[Karl Blossfeldt]], German photographer (d. 1932)\n*  1865   &ndash; [[W. B. Yeats]], Irish poet and playwright, [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 1939)\n*[[1868]] &ndash; [[Wallace Clement Sabine]], American physicist and academic (d. 1919)\n*[[1870]] &ndash; [[Jules Bordet]], Belgian immunologist and microbiologist, [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 1961)\n*[[1872]] &ndash; [[Thomas N. Heffron]], American actor, director, and screenwriter (d. 1951)\n*[[1873]] &ndash; [[Karin Swanstr\u00f6m]], Swedish actress, director, and producer (d. 1942)\n*[[1875]] &ndash; [[Paul Neumann (swimmer)|Paul Neumann]], Austrian swimmer and physician (d. 1932)\n*[[1876]] &ndash; [[William Sealy Gosset]], English chemist and statistician (d. 1937)\n*[[1879]] &ndash; [[Heinrich Gutkin]], Estonian businessman and politician (d. 1941)\n*  1879   &ndash; [[Charalambos Tseroulis]], Greek general and politician, [[List of defence ministers of Greece|Greek Minister for Military Affairs]] (d. 1929)\n*[[1884]] &ndash; [[Leon Chwistek]], Polish painter, philosopher, and mathematician (d. 1944)\n*  1884   &ndash; [[\u00c9tienne Gilson]], French philosopher and academic (d. 1978)\n*[[1885]] &ndash; [[Henry George Lamond]], Australian farmer and author (d. 1969)\n*[[1887]] &ndash; [[Andr\u00e9 Fran\u00e7ois-Poncet]], French politician and diplomat (d. 1978)\n*  1887   &ndash; [[Bruno Frank]], German-American author, poet, and playwright (d. 1945)\n*[[1888]] &ndash; [[Fernando Pessoa]], Portuguese poet and critic (d. 1935)\n*[[1892]] &ndash; [[Basil Rathbone]], South African-born British-American actor (d. 1967)\n*[[1893]] &ndash; [[Alan Arnold Griffith]], English engineer (d. 1963)\n*  1893   &ndash; [[Dorothy L. Sayers]], English author and poet (d. 1957)\n*[[1894]] &ndash; [[Leo Kanner]], Ukrainian-American psychiatrist and physician (d. 1981)\n*  1894   &ndash; [[Jacques Henri Lartigue]], French photographer and painter (d. 1986)\n*[[1897]] &ndash; [[Paavo Nurmi]], Finnish runner and coach (d. 1973)\n*[[1899]] &ndash; [[Carlos Ch\u00e1vez]], Mexican composer, conductor, and journalist, founded the [[Mexican Symphonic Orchestra]] (d. 1978)\n*[[1901]] &ndash; [[Tage Erlander]], Swedish lieutenant and politician, 25th [[Prime Minister of Sweden]] (d. 1985)\n*[[1902]] &ndash; [[Carolyn Eisele]], American mathematician and historian (d. 2000)\n*[[1903]] &ndash; [[Willard Harrison Bennett]], American physicist and chemist (d. 1987)\n*[[1905]] &ndash; [[James T. Rutnam]], Sri Lankan historian and author (d. 1988)\n*[[1906]] &ndash; [[Bruno de Finetti]], Austrian-Italian mathematician and statistician (d. 1985)\n*[[1909]] &ndash; [[E. M. S. Namboodiripad]], Indian theorist and politician, 1st [[Chief Minister of Kerala]] (d. 1998)\n*[[1910]] &ndash; [[Gonzalo Torrente Ballester]], Spanish journalist, author, and playwright (d. 1999)\n*  1910   &ndash; [[Mary Wickes]], American actress (d. 1995)\n*  1910   &ndash; [[Mary Whitehouse]], English activist, founded the [[National Viewers' and Listeners' Association]] (d. 2001)\n*[[1911]] &ndash; [[Luis Walter Alvarez]], American physicist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 1988)\n*  1911   &ndash; [[Maurice Copeland]], American actor (d. 1985)\n*  1911   &ndash; [[Erwin Wilhelm M\u00fcller]], German physicist and academic (d. 1977)\n*[[1912]] &ndash; [[Hector de Saint-Denys Garneau]], Canadian poet and painter (d. 1943)\n*[[1913]] &ndash; [[Ralph Edwards]], American radio and television host (d. 2005)\n*  1913   &ndash; [[Yitzhak Pundak]], Israeli general, diplomat and politician (d. 2017)\n*[[1914]] &ndash; [[Frederic Franklin]], English-American ballet dancer and director (d. 2013)\n*[[1915]] &ndash; [[Don Budge]], American tennis player and coach (d. 2000)\n*[[1916]] &ndash; [[Wu Zhengyi]], Chinese botanist and academic (d. 2013)\n*[[1917]] &ndash; [[Teddy Turner (actor)|Teddy Turner]], English actor (d. 1992)\n*  1917   &ndash; [[Augusto Roa Bastos]], Paraguayan novelist (d. 2005)\n*[[1918]] &ndash; [[Ben Johnson (actor)|Ben Johnson]], American actor and stuntman (d. 1996)\n*  1918   &ndash; [[Helmut Lent]], German soldier and pilot (d. 1944)\n*  1918   &ndash; [[Percy Rodriguez]], Canadian-American actor (d. 2007)\n*[[1920]] &ndash; [[Rolf Huisgen]], German chemist and academic\n*  1920   &ndash; [[Iosif Vorovich]], Russian mathematician and engineer (d. 2001)\n*[[1921]] &ndash; [[Lennart Strand]], Swedish runner (d. 2004)\n*[[1922]] &ndash; [[Etienne Leroux]], South African author (d. 1989)\n*[[1923]] &ndash; [[Lloyd Conover]], American chemist and inventor (d. 2017)\n*[[1925]] &ndash; [[Kristine Miller]], American actress (d. 2015)\n*[[1926]] &ndash; [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Lejeune]], French pediatrician and geneticist (d. 1994)\n*  1926   &ndash; [[Paul Lynde]], American actor and comedian (d. 1982)\n*[[1927]] &ndash; [[Slim Dusty]], Australian singer-songwriter and guitarist (d. 2003)\n*[[1928]] &ndash; [[Giacomo Biffi]], Italian cardinal (d. 2015)\n*  1928   &ndash; [[Ren\u00e9e Morisset]], Canadian pianist (d. 2009)\n*  1928   &ndash; [[John Forbes Nash, Jr.]], American mathematician and academic, [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 2015)\n*[[1929]] &ndash; [[Ralph McQuarrie]], American illustrator (d. 2012)\n*  1929   &ndash; [[Robert W. Scott]], American farmer and politician, 67th [[Governor of North Carolina]] (d. 2009)\n*[[1930]] &ndash; [[Gotthard Graubner]], German painter and educator (d. 2013)\n*  1930   &ndash; [[Ryszard Kukli\u0144ski]], Polish colonel and spy (d. 2004)\n*  1930   &ndash; [[Paul Veyne]], French archaeologist, historian, and academic\n*[[1931]] &ndash; [[Nora Kovach]], Hungarian-American ballerina (d. 2009)\n*  1931   &ndash; [[Reed Scowen]], Canadian politician\n*  1931   &ndash; [[Irvin D. Yalom]], American psychotherapist and academic\n*[[1932]] &ndash; [[Raymond Jolliffe, 5th Baron Hylton]], English politician\n*  1932   &ndash; [[Bob McGrath]], American singer and actor ([[Sesame Street]])\n*  1932   &ndash; [[Billy Williams (right fielder)|Billy Williams]], American baseball player and coach (d. 2013)\n*[[1933]] &ndash; [[Tom King, Baron King of Bridgwater]], English soldier and politician, [[Secretary of State for Defence]]\n*  1933   &ndash; [[Norman Lloyd-Edwards]], Welsh lawyer and politician, [[Lord Lieutenant of South Glamorgan]]\n*[[1934]] &ndash; [[Bill Blakeley]], American basketball player and coach (d. 2010)\n*  1934   &ndash; [[Lucjan Brychczy]], Polish footballer and coach\n*  1934   &ndash; [[Manuel Clouthier]], Mexican businessman and politician (d. 1989)\n*  1934   &ndash; [[James Anthony Griffin]], American bishop\n*  1934   &ndash; [[Uriel Jones]], American drummer (d. 2009)\n*  1934   &ndash; [[Leonard Kleinrock]], American computer scientist and engineer\n*[[1935]] &ndash; [[Christo]], Bulgarian-French sculptor and painter\n*  1935   &ndash; [[Jeanne-Claude]], Moroccan sculptor and painter (d. 2009)\n*  1935   &ndash; [[Samak Sundaravej]], Thai politician, 25th [[Prime Minister of Thailand]] (d. 2009)\n*[[1937]] &ndash; [[Eleanor Holmes Norton]], American lawyer and politician\n*  1937   &ndash; [[Erich Ribbeck]], German footballer and manager\n*  1937   &ndash; [[Andreas Whittam Smith]], English journalist and publisher, co-founded ''[[The Independent]]''\n*[[1940]] &ndash; [[Bobby Freeman]], American singer-songwriter, pianist, and producer (d. 2017)\n*  1940   &ndash; [[Dallas Long]], American shot putter and physician\n*[[1941]] &ndash; [[Marcel Lachemann]], American baseball player, coach, and manager\n*  1941   &ndash; [[Serge Lemoyne]], Canadian painter (d. 1998)\n*  1941   &ndash; [[Marv Tarplin]], American guitarist and songwriter (d. 2011)\n*[[1942]] &ndash; [[Yiannis Boutaris]], Greek businessman and politician, [[List of mayors of Thessaloniki|Mayor of Thessaloniki]]\n*[[1943]] &ndash; [[Harry Collins]], English sociologist, author, and academic\n*  1943   &ndash; [[Malcolm McDowell]], English actor and producer\n*  1943   &ndash; [[Jim Guy Tucker]],  American lawyer and politician, 43rd [[Governor of Arkansas]]\n*[[1944]] &ndash; [[Christine Beasley]], English nursing administrator\n*  1944   &ndash; [[David Curry]], English journalist and politician, [[Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]]\n*  1944   &ndash; [[Ban Ki-moon]], South Korean politician and diplomat, 8th [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]]\n*[[1945]] &ndash; [[Whitley Strieber]], American author\n*[[1946]] &ndash; [[Sher Bahadur Deuba]], Nepalese politician, 32nd [[Prime Minister of Nepal]]\n*  1946   &ndash; [[Paul L. Modrich]], American biochemist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] laureate\n*  1946   &ndash; [[Gabriel of Komana]], Belgian-Dutch archbishop (d. 2013)\n*[[1948]] &ndash; [[Garnet Bailey]], Canadian-American ice hockey player and scout (d. 2001)\n*  1948   &ndash; [[Joe Roth]], American director and producer, co-founded [[Morgan Creek Productions]]\n*[[1949]] &ndash; [[Ann Druyan]], American popular science writer\n*  1949   &ndash; [[Dennis Locorriere]], American singer and musician ([[Dr. Hook]]) \n*  1949   &ndash; [[Ulla Schmidt]], German educator and politician, [[Federal Ministry of Health (Germany)|German Federal Minister of Health]]\n*  1949   &ndash; [[Red Symons]], English-Australian musician, television, and radio personality\n*[[1950]] &ndash; [[Nick Brown]], English politician, [[Minister of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]]\n*  1950   &ndash; [[Gerd Zewe]], German footballer and manager\n*[[1951]] &ndash; [[Howard Leese]], American guitarist and producer\n*  1951   &ndash; [[Richard Thomas (actor)|Richard Thomas]], American actor, director, and producer\n*  1951   &ndash; [[Stellan Skarsg\u00e5rd]], Swedish actor \n*[[1952]] &ndash; [[Jean-Marie Dedecker]], Belgian martial artist and politician\n*[[1953]] &ndash; [[Tim Allen]], American actor, comedian, and producer\n*[[1954]] &ndash; [[Andrzej Lepper]], Polish politician, [[Deputy Prime Minister of the Republic of Poland]] (d. 2011)\n*  1954   &ndash; [[Ngozi Okonjo-Iweala]], Nigerian economist and politician, [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Nigeria)|Minister of Foreign Affairs for Nigeria]]\n*[[1955]] &ndash; 